Response to
Episode 3 - "When Knowledge Conquered Fear"
@-------------------------------------------------
==================
Comments:
==================
- Much like episode 1, episode 3 discusses the history of humans and astronomy. But in this episode, it goes more in depth about the human perception of astronomical events

====================
What I learned:
====================
- Humans evolved pattern recognition over hundreds of generations

- Our early ancestors looked up at the stars to direct their lives, and assumed that whatever happened in the sky was directed towards them
  *So when they saw comets, they took it as a bad sign

- Jan Oort, a Dutch astronomer in 1950s concluded that comets needed to come from a sphere of comets surrounding the sun, known as the Oort cloud
  *He was the first to map the Milky Way and our position in the Milky Way

- Edmond Halley, an English astronomer in the 17th century, was not fearful of comets like those at his time
  *He was the first to make a complete star map of the Southern Hemisphere
  *Made the first map of the Earth's magnetic field
  *Perfected the diving bell
  *Invented the weather map
  *Measured distance from Earth to the Sun
  *etc...

- Robert Hooke, an English scientist, discovered the cell with his own invention, the compound microscope
  *Developed law of elasticity (Hooke's law)
  *Perfected the air pump
  *etc...

- Isaac Newton despised his family life (especially his stepfather), but loved to understand nature
  *Went to Cambridge where he was a lousy student with no friends
  *Studied alchemy, hoping to change regular metals to gold or silver
  *Searched for secret messages in many translations of the Bible
  *Hooke accused Newton of stealing his discoveries about light, which wasn't true
  *Newton sent Hooke a letter detailing his mathematical calculations of planetary motion
  *Halley was determined to bring Newton's knowledge to the world, helping to publish Newton's "Principia"
  *Hooke continued to steal Newton's ideas, until Newton and Halley confronted him
  *Newton believed it was possible to overcome gravity, the basis of space travel

- Many of the theories about the future of the universe stem from Halley, who used Newton's laws to predict the path of Halley's comet, and much more

